The paper presents a new algorithm for learning distributed node representations in a graph, which is a common task in network analysis and machine learning. The algorithm is designed to be scalable and performant, which suggests that it may be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the construction of a node similarity matrix and the use of dimension reduction techniques, which are common topics in sub-categories such as cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper evaluates the algorithm on several real-world networks, which suggests that it may be relevant to sub-category cs.DB (Databases).
